</p>

<p>The death of a child is an unimaginable tragedy, leaving a void that can never truly be filled.  Offering condolences during such a time is not about fixing the situation, but about acknowledging the immense pain and offering a supportive presence.  A thoughtful message, delivered with care, can provide a small measure of comfort and let the bereaved know they are not alone in their grief.  It's crucial to remember that there are no perfect words, but genuine sympathy and empathy are paramount. Choosing the right words, delivering your message with sensitivity, and respecting the grieving process are key.</p>
<p>Appropriate etiquette involves avoiding clichés or platitudes, focusing instead on sincere expressions of empathy and support.  Whether you knew the child personally or not, your heartfelt message can offer solace.  Consider the relationship you had with the bereaved; a close friend might warrant a longer, more personal message, while a colleague may appreciate a shorter, more formal expression of sympathy.  Delivery should be thoughtful—a handwritten note often feels more personal than an email, though a phone call can provide immediate support.</p>
    

